Theorie

Vapnik fÃ¼hrte in (Vladimir Vapnik 2020) zwei neue Riskofunktion ein. Die erste neue Risikofunktion, mit rearrangement by me:

\[ R = \frac{1}{n}\,\mathbf{r}^{T}\,\mathbf{V}\,\mathbf{r} \\ \mathbf{r} = \mathbf{y} - \hat{\mathbf{y}} \\ \hat{\mathbf{y}} = h(\mathbf{x}) \]

und der \(n \times n\) quadratic matrix \(\mathbf{V}\), deren EintrÃ¤ge lauten:

\[ v_{ij}(x_i, x_j) = \sum_{s=1}^n G(x_s - x_i)\,G(x_s - x_j) \]

The kernel function is such that the matrix \(\mathbf{V}\) becomes the unity matrix \(\mathbf{I}\) and the risk becomes the usual mean squared error:

\[ R = \frac{1}{n}\,\mathbf{r}^{T}\,\mathbf{I}\,\mathbf{r} = \frac{1}{n}\,\mathbf{r}^{T}\,\mathbf{r} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2 \]

Question: can we extend this to multi-respone? The gaussian law for error propagation would

\[ \mathcal{R} = \frac{1}{n}\,\mathbf{R}^T\,\mathbf{V}\,\mathbf{R} \\ \mathbf{R} = \mathbf{Y} - \hat{\mathbf{Y}} \\ \hat{\mathbf{Y}} = h(\mathbf{X}) \]

For \(\mathbf{V} = \mathbf{I}\), the risk \(\mathcal{R}\) becomes the variance-covariance matrix. How using it for optimization?

The diagonal elements of the \(\mathcal{R}\) matrix are the risks of the respective classes. The secondary diagonal elements are the co-risks between any two classes.

Beispiel kernel function G for uni-variate explanatory variable

\[ G(z) = \exp\left[-\frac{z^2}{2\,\sigma^2}\right] \]

G <- function(z, s2 = 0.1) exp(-z^2/s2)

get_V <- function(x, G, ...)
{
  # prepare output object
  n <- length(x)
  V <- matrix(ncol = n, nrow = n)
  # compute V matrix
  for (i in seq_len(n)) {
    Gi <- G(x - x[i], ...)
    for (j in seq_len(n)) {
      Gj <- G(x - x[j], ...)
      V[i,j] <- sum(Gi*Gj)
    }
  }
  # return V matrix
  V
}

Beispiel 1: Regression

data_generator <- function(n)
{
  x <- runif(n, min = 0, max = 10)
  y <- 2*sin(x) + 1*x + rnorm(n, mean = 0, sd = 0.5)
  data.frame(x = x,
             y = y)
}
set.seed(42)
df_train <- data_generator(60)
plot(df_train)

df <- data_generator(10)

Risk function

emp_risk <- function(y, pred_y, V)
{
  r <- y - pred_y
  n <- length(r)
  risk <- (r %*% V %*% r) / n
  as.numeric(risk)
}

Hypothesis function

h <- function(x, w)
{
  #w[1] + w[2]*x + w[3]*x^2 + w[4]*x^3 + w[5]*x^4 + w[6]*x^5
  sum <- 0
  for (i in seq_along(w))
    sum <- sum + w[i]*x^(i - 1)
  sum
}

Driver function

func <- function(par, df, V)
{
  pred_y <- h(df$x, par)
  emp_risk(df$y, pred_y, V)
}

Function for Optim mit V-Matrix.

optim_func <- function(init_par, df_train, driver_func, G, ...)
{
  optim(
    par     = init_par,
    fn      = driver_func, 
    gr      = NULL,
    df_train, get_V(df_train$x, G, ...),
    method  = "BFGS",
    control = list(maxit = 5e6)
  )
}
MSE <- function(y, pred_y)
{
  mean((y - pred_y)^2)
}
df_test <- data_generator(1e6)
s2_vec <- c(10^seq(-9,-5), 1:9*1e-4, 10^seq(-3,1))
results <- vector(mode = "list", length(s2_vec))
MSE_test <- rep(NA, length(s2_vec))
start_pars <- runif(6, min = -1, max = 1)
for (i in seq_along(s2_vec)) {
  # do the fit/training
  fit <- optim_func(start_pars, df_train, func, G, s2_vec[i])
  if (fit$convergence != 0) 
    cat("Convergence problems in", i, ". round :", fit$convergence, "\n")
  # compute test error and print results
  MSE_test[i] <- MSE(df_test$y, h(df_test$x, fit$par))
  cat(i, "round; s2 =", s2_vec[i], 
      "; MSE test =", MSE_test[i], "\n")
  # cold or warm start for next fit
  #start_pars <- runif(6, min = -1, max = 1)
  start_pars <- fit$par
  # store current fit
  results[[i]] <- fit
}
